# SwiftFormat owns layout. Pinned here so the canonical style lives in the repo
# rather than in whatever editor hook happens to be installed — without this file
# a machine without the hook formats differently and nothing notices.
#
# Division of labour with SwiftLint (.swiftlint.yml):
#   SwiftFormat  — whitespace, braces, wrapping, import order. Runs with --fix.
#   SwiftLint    — defects, complexity, dead weight, idioms. Never reformats.
# Where the two could overlap, this file is configured so SwiftLint's *default*
# formatting rules pass, and SwiftLint's opt-in formatting rules stay off.
#
# Note on braces: SwiftLint ships two mutually exclusive rules. `opening_brace`
# (a default) wants `{` on the declaration line; `contrasted_opening_brace`
# (opt-in) wants it on its own line. They cannot both be satisfied. We keep the
# default, idiomatic-Swift one — which is also why ~298 of the "violations" from
# enabling every opt-in rule were noise rather than debt.

--swiftversion 5.0
--indent 4
--maxwidth 130          # matches line_length in .swiftlint.yml

# Keep `{` on the signature line even when the signature wraps, so SwiftLint's
# default opening_brace rule passes. This is the one setting that was silently
# disagreeing with SwiftLint before.

# Wrapping
--wraparguments before-first
--wrapparameters before-first
--wrapcollections before-first
--closingparen balanced

# Redundancy — these mirror SwiftLint rules we enable, so --fix resolves them.
--self remove
--stripunusedargs closure-only

# Keep the diff honest: don't rewrite comments or reorder declarations.

# Satisfy SwiftLint's `attributes` rule: @objc/@MainActor on their own line for
# funcs and types, inline for vars.
--funcattributes prev-line
--typeattributes prev-line
--varattributes same-line

# Satisfy SwiftLint's `vertical_whitespace_between_cases`.

# Satisfy SwiftLint's `conditional_returns_on_newline` and friends: inline
# conditional bodies get wrapped onto their own line.

# Wrapped `guard`/`if` conditions indent by one level instead of aligning under
# the first condition, so every line stays a multiple of the indent width
# (SwiftLint's `indentation_width`).
--wrapconditions before-first

# SwiftFormat's numberFormatting was stripping the underscores SwiftLint's
# `number_separator` requires. Group decimals from four digits up so both agree.
--decimalgrouping 3,4

# SwiftFormat's redundantRawValues strips raw values that match the case name —
# exactly what SwiftLint's `explicit_enum_raw_value` requires. These raw values
# reach the user's config file on disk, so being explicit is the point.

# redundantInternal, redundantExtensionACL and extensionAccessControl all strip explicit `internal`,
# which explicit_acl requires. With redundantRawValues and numberFormatting that
# makes five SwiftFormat rules that silently undo a SwiftLint requirement — this
# is the first place to look when a lint rule refuses to stay satisfied.
#
# NOTE: SwiftFormat keeps only the LAST --disable / --enable line, so these must
# be single comma-separated lists. Splitting them across lines silently drops all
# but the final one — which is how explicit enum raw values kept getting stripped.
--disable wrapMultilineStatementBraces,wrapEnumCases,organizeDeclarations,blankLinesAroundMark,redundantRawValues,redundantInternal,redundantExtensionACL,extensionAccessControl
--enable sortImports,blankLineAfterSwitchCase,wrapConditionalBodies,wrapLoopBodies,consistentSwitchCaseSpacing
